    <div>
        <h1>THE ORCHESTRA</h1>
    </div>
    <article class="container-text">
        <div>
            <img src=""/>
        </div>
        <div>
            <p>The Symphony Orchestra of Rio Grande do Norte was created by Decree No. 6874 of March 1976, signed by then Governor Tarcisio Maia, through the initiative of at the time, Secretary of Education and Culture, Professor João Faustino, now belong to the tables the same administrative Secretariat.</p>
            <p>The first concert was held on March 11, 1977, and had as conductor Pernambuco Mario Justo Cancio dos Santos, which organized and conducted the orchestra for about 10 years. The orchestra began with a staff of 23 effective musicians, of which only five lived in the city of Natal, and performed a baroque and chamber music repertoire.</p>
            <p>The first tender for joining the Symphony Orchestra takes place in 1988 in the then management Governor Geraldo Melo. Thus, the orchestra was expanded and now has 60 musicians. Around this time the violinist and teacher Osvaldo D'Amore became the new conductor of the orchestra, a position in which he remained for almost 20 years.</p>
            <p>The orchestra has since gone to do successful work presenting official concerts at the Teatro Alberto Maranhão, external popular concerts, educational concerts for the entire school system, as well as special concerts in the state. The OSRN has recorded three CDs, including one with the participation of artists Sivuca, Canhoto da Paraíba, Moraes Moreira and Henrique Cazes.</p>
            <p>Since its founding, the Symphony Orchestra received the collaboration of several managing directors. The first was Zuleika Roman, who was in office during the entire period of the then conductor Mario Cancio. Later assumed the position: Selma Sa, Diana Fontes, Olga Aranha Deijair Borges, Candinha Bezerra, Gina Cavalcanti, Fidja Siqueira, Paulo Henrique de Lima (first musician holder OSRN to hold the position), Francisco José Alves, Maria das Dores, and currently Luiz Antonio Paiva (first musician holder OSRN chosen directly by their peers).</p>
            <p>In 2007 he took over as conductor of the Symphony Orchestra, the Conductor André Muniz; in 2011 he took over for a short period the Regent Pe Pedro Ferreira; and in September 2012 took over the current conductor Linus Lerner. In the current season of 2016, OSRN runs a project with conductors and guest soloists, national and international, which provides an immeasurable musical growth for members of OSRN musicians, as each guest professional shares with the orchestra his musical conception, your experience artistic and interpretation for each performed work.</p>
            <p>Currently the orchestra has 60 musicians who rehearse daily in the Children's Town, the OSRN headquarters, and continues with all hard to do a much educational work with the formation of new audiences, the broadcast quality of music, be it classical or popular. A short work of importance to the cultural development of the State of Rio Grande do Norte.</p>
        </div>
